This paper presents a secure steganographic method based on chaos-aided quantization index modulation (QIM). By integrating chaotic dynamics with lattice-based quantization, the proposed scheme enhances security while preserving the statistical properties of the cover signal. A chaotic system generates a pseudorandom sequence, which is transformed into a uniform distribution via modulo lattice operations. This sequence then serves as a dither signal in the QIM embedding process, ensuring that the stego signals remain indistinguishable from the original. We provide formal proof of statistical indistinguishability. Theoretical and experimental results confirm that the chaos-aided QIM approach resists statistical detection while maintaining high embedding efficiency. The method is particularly suited for applications requiring undetectable covert communication.